27. Recommended Relationships
- One exam has many subjects.
- One subject has many chapters.
- One chapter has many topics.
- One topic has many learning contents.
- One topic has many questions.
- One test has many questions.
- One test attempt has many answers.
- One user has many bookmarks, notes, attempts, and submissions.
- One submission has many moderation logs.

28. Indexing Recommendations
Add indexes on:
- user_id.
- exam_id.
- subject_id.
- chapter_id.
- topic_id.
- status.
- created_at.
- published_at.
- event_name.
- notification read state.

29. Migration Strategy
- Start with core tables first.
- Add analytics and AI tables later.
- Use seeders for base exams, subjects, and chapters.
- Keep schema version-controlled.
- Avoid destructive migrations in production without backups.

30. Future Extensions
- Multi-language content tables.
- Subscription and billing tables.
- Coupon and referral tables.
- Instructor and class management tables.
- Offline sync tables.
- Adaptive learning recommendation tables.

31. Schema Summary
The schema should support a scalable exam prep product by separating study content, user progress, test mechanics, community workflows, and analytics into clear relational structures.

